'''Sat Thai''' ({{lang-th|<U+0E2A><U+0E32><U+0E23><U+0E17><U+0E44><U+0E17><U+0E22>}}, also spelled '''Sart Thai''') is a traditional [[Thailand|Thai]] mid-year festival, held on the new moon at the end of the tenth [[Thai lunar calendar|lunar month]]. It has many features of [[animism]], attributing [[soul]]s or [[spirit]]s to [[animal]]s, [[plant]]s and other entities.

== Etymology ==
''Sat'' ({{lang|th|<U+0E28><U+0E32><U+0E23><U+0E17>}} or {{lang|th|<U+0E2A><U+0E32><U+0E23><U+0E17> (<U+0E2A><U+0E32><U+0E17>)}}, RTGS 'Sat') comes from [[Pali]] {{transl|IAST|s<U+0101>rada}}, which means ''autumnal''.<ref>Turner: page 718, <U+015B><U+0101>rad<U+00E1> 12402</ref> It specifically refers to the [[season]] "when the grain is in the ear": rice grain panicles droop as seed reaches full size and fills with milky starch in the days before harvest time. Fruits also are in the bud.

''Sat Thai'' is known as such to differentiate it from the [[Ghost Festival]], known in Thai as ''Sat Chin''.

==Observance==
''Sat Thai'' Day occurs at the end of [[Thai lunar calendar]] Moon 10, that is, waning day 15, evening ({{lang|th|<U+0E27><U+0E31><U+0E19><U+0E41><U+0E23><U+0E21>  <U+0E51><U+0E55>  <U+0E04><U+0E48><U+0E33>  <U+0E40><U+0E14><U+0E37><U+0E2D><U+0E19>  <U+0E51><U+0E50>}}). This is a New Moon and so is a [[Buddhist]] [[Uposatha|Sabbath]]; but not one of the ''Special Sabbaths'', and not one of the [[secular]] [[public holidays in Thailand]]. It occurs midway past the traditional [[Thai New Year]] and near the [[autumnal equinox]]. It an occasion for [[making merit]] by honoring ({{lang|th|<U+0E1A><U+0E39><U+0E0A><U+0E32>}} buucha) the spirits of the season, as well as one's deceased relatives, according to local [[tradition]], with various [[rite]]s and [[ceremony|ceremonies]].

== Beginning of the Vegetarian Festival ==
{{main|Vegetarian Festival}}
''Sat Thai'' Day usually corresponds with the beginning of the nine-day Vegetarian Festival, which is widely observed by [[Thai Chinese]] and some Thais. It appears on calendars as "Begin 9-day vegetarian festival" (''roem thet-sa-gan kin-che 9 wan'', {{lang|th|<U+0E40><U+0E23><U+0E34><U+0E48><U+0E21><U+0E40><U+0E17><U+0E28><U+0E01><U+0E32><U+0E25><U+0E01><U+0E34><U+0E19><U+0E40><U+0E08> <U+0E55> <U+0E27><U+0E31><U+0E19>}}) <U+2014> ''kin-che'' ({{lang|th|<U+0E01><U+0E34><U+0E19><U+0E40><U+0E08>}}) is to vow in the manner of Vietnamese or Chinese Buddhists to eat a strict vegetarian diet.) <ref>[http://rirs3.royin.go.th/dictionary.asp Online Royal Institute Dictionary]</ref>

